abstract: Jho Low, the financier charged with looting billions from a Malaysian fund, had an audience in 2012 with Lloyd C. Blankfein, the chairman and chief executive of Goldman Sachs.
snippet: Jho Low, the financier charged with looting billions from a Malaysian fund, had an audience in 2012 with Lloyd C. Blankfein, the chairman and chief executive of Goldman Sachs.
lead_paragraph: One day in December 2012, a young Malaysian V.I.P. entered the gleaming headquarters of Goldman Sachs in Lower Manhattan. The man, Jho Low, a financier with close ties to Malaysia’s prime minister at the time, was there for a private meeting with one of the most powerful people on Wall Street: Goldman’s longtime chairman and chief executive, Lloyd C. Blankfein.

headline_main: German Plays Tackle the World’s Woes, Current and Future

abstract: In a Kansas City park, a health inspector poured bleach on food donated to homeless people. The volunteers didn’t meet city requirements, the inspector said.
snippet: In a Kansas City park, a health inspector poured bleach on food donated to homeless people. The volunteers didn’t meet city requirements, the inspector said.
lead_paragraph: KANSAS CITY, Mo. — They unfurled colorful blankets on a grassy slope, and unloaded steaming trays of corn dogs, baked beans and vegetable beef soup. Every week for the past three years, the volunteers have gone to a park just outside downtown Kansas City with home-cooked meals for the homeless. They call it a picnic with friends.

abstract: Suggested reading from critics and editors at The New York Times.
snippet: Suggested reading from critics and editors at The New York Times.
lead_paragraph: As America heads into the long Thanksgiving weekend, let’s pause a moment to express our gratitude for books and the people who write them. We’ve got some good recommendations this week, anchored by a number of smart genre novels: a serial killer (“My Sister, the Serial Killer,” by Oyinkan Braithwaite), a feral detective (“The Feral Detective,” by Jonathan Lethem), a Japanese Sherlock Holmes (“Newcomer,” by Keigo Higashino). There’s also poetry and dystopia and history and science, and a couple of takes on the state of American Judaism — something for everyone, even your angry Uncle Bot. Happy reading, and enjoy the holiday.

abstract: Russia has tried to use Interpol to silence critics, and rights groups fear increased Kremlin influence. American and European officials are trying to block a Russian presidency.
snippet: Russia has tried to use Interpol to silence critics, and rights groups fear increased Kremlin influence. American and European officials are trying to block a Russian presidency.
lead_paragraph: BRUSSELS — Gathered at a glitzy Dubai resort this week for their annual conference, the leaders of Interpol hoped to emerge from the shadow of the controversy that erupted after Beijing snatched the agency’s Chinese president and unilaterally announced his resignation.
